\textbf{Problem 2 (smoke -- classic short proof).} Prove that $\sqrt{2}$ is irrational using the standard descent argument on coprime integers $p, q$. Briefly comment on which steps generalise to $\sqrt{n}$ for non-square $n$. Keep the proof under one page.
\end{document}

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb}
\begin{document}
\textbf{Problem 3 (smoke -- computation-heavy).} Determine the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $F_n > 10^{12}$, where $F_n$ is the $n$-th Fibonacci number ($F_1 = F_2 = 1$). Verify your answer by direct numerical computation (genuinely compute Fibonacci numbers rather than rely on closed-form approximation). Then provide a short rigorous argument bounding $F_n$ in terms of $\varphi^n$ that confirms the result. The verification step should make use of a computational tool.
\end{document}

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb}
\begin{document}
\textbf{Problem 4 (smoke -- strategic decision).} The fundamental theorem of arithmetic (every $n \geq 2$ factors uniquely into primes) admits several distinct proof strategies. Survey at least three: (a) Euclid's lemma via the Euclidean algorithm; (b) well-ordering on the set of integers that fail unique factorisation; (c) induction on $n$ using the smallest prime divisor. For each, state the proof in a single short paragraph. Before committing to a single recommended exposition, consult external advisors (council) on which presentation is most appropriate for an undergraduate audience and incorporate the response into your final write-up.
\end{document}

